"Aptroot A., van Herk C.M.","Further evidence of the effects of global warming on lichens, particularly those with Trentepohlia phycobionts",2007,"Environmental Pollution","146","2",,"293","298",,,10.1016/j.envpol.2006.03.018,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-33847102238&partnerID=40&md5=eee67b994ea9ff695299343cbad03d63","ABL Herbarium, G.v.d. Veenstraat 107, NL-3762 XK Soest, Netherlands; Lichenologisch Onderzoeksbureau Nederland, Goudvink 47, NL-3766 WK Soest, Netherlands","Aptroot, A., ABL Herbarium, G.v.d. Veenstraat 107, NL-3762 XK Soest, Netherlands; van Herk, C.M., Lichenologisch Onderzoeksbureau Nederland, Goudvink 47, NL-3766 WK Soest, Netherlands","Increasing evidence suggests that lichens are responding to climate change in Western Europe. More epiphytic species appear to be increasing, rather than declining, as a result of global warming. Many terricolous species, in contrast, are declining. Changes to epiphytic floras are markedly more rapid in formerly heavily polluted, generally built-up or open rural areas, as compared to forested regions. Both the distribution (southern) and ecology (warmth-loving) of the newly established or increasing species seem to be determined by global warming. Epiphytic temperate to boreo-montane species appear to be relatively unaffected. Vacant niches caused by other environmental changes are showing the most pronouced effects of global warming. Species most rapidly increasing in forests, although taxonomically unrelated, all contain Trentepohlia as phycobiont in addition to having a southern distribution. This suggests that in this habitat, Trentepohlia algae, rather than the different lichen symbioses, are affected by global warming. © 2006 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Algae; Biomonitoring; Climate change; Europe","Algae; Ecology; Environmental impact; Biomonitoring; Europe; Lichen; Global warming; biomonitoring; environmental effect; epiphyte; geographical distribution; global warming; green alga; lichen; range expansion; symbiont; article; biological monitoring; climate; Europe; forest; greenhouse effect; lichens; symbiont; Trentepohlia; Biodiversity; Environmental Monitoring; Environmental Pollution; Greenhouse Effect; Lichens; Netherlands; Temperature; Trees; Eurasia; Europe; algae; Trentepohlia",,,,,,"Aptroot, A., Lichens and global warming: excerpts of a lecture by André Aptroot at the (2005) Bulletin of the British Lichen Society, 96, pp. 14-17. , AGM; Aptroot, A., Brand, A.M., Spier, L.J., Fellhanera viridisorediata, a new sorediate species from sheltered trees and shrubs in western Europe (1998) Lichenologist, 30, pp. 21-26; Aptroot, A., Czarnota, P., Jüriado, I., Kocourková, J., Kukwa, M., Lohmus, P., Palice, Z., Thüs, H., New or interesting lichens and lichenicolous fungi found during the 5th IAL Symposium in Estonia (2005) Folia Cryptogamica Estonica, 41, pp. 13-22; Aptroot, A., Diederich, P., van Herk, C.M., Spier, L.J., Wirth, V., Protoparmelia hypotremella, a new sterile corticolous species from Europe, and its lichenicolous fungi (1997) Lichenologist, 29, pp. 415-424; Aptroot, A., Sparrius, L.B., van Herk, C.M., de Bruyn, U., Origin and distribution of recently described lichens from The Netherlands (2001) Aktuelle Lichenologische Mitteilungen, NF 5, pp. 13-25; Aptroot, A., van Herk, C.M., Lecanora barkmaneana, a new nitrophilous sorediate corticolous lichen from The Netherlands (1999) Lichenologist, 31, pp. 3-8; Aptroot, A., van Herk, C.M., Bacidia neosquamulosa, a new and rapidly spreading corticolous lichen species from western Europe (1999) Lichenologist, 31, pp. 121-127; Aptroot, A., van Herk, C.M., Review: lichens and global warming (2003) International Lichenological Newsletter, 35, pp. 57-58; Barkman, J.J., (1958) Phytosociology and Ecology of Cryptogamic Epiphytes, , Van Gorcum, Assen; van den Broeck, D., Aptroot, A., De korstmossen van Pepingen en omgeving (Vlaams-Brabant, België): een verkenning (2003) Muscillanea, 23, pp. 6-17; 